},"en":{"1760–06 Nov 1817":"about 1760–6 November 1817","1759–1820":"1759–1820","1800–1870":"about1800–1870","1806–Male":"1806–Deceased","1806–Female":"1806–Deceased","1760–1817":"about1760–1817","06 Nov 1817":"6 November 1817","1791":"1791","1800":"about 1800","1811":"1811","1777":"1777","1776":"1776","1820":"1820","1795":"1795","1760":"about 1760","1870":"1870","1808":"1808","1806":"1806","1817":"1817","1759":"1759","Savannah, Chatham, Georgia, United States of America":"Savannah, Chatham, Georgia, United States","South Carolina, United States":"South Carolina, United States","Georgia, United States":"Georgia, United States","nameMeanings":[{"name":"MARY","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Old French <i>Marie</i>.  See  <b>Mary</b>   ."],"variants":[{"name":"Moira","meanings":["Anglicized form of Irish Máire , now used throughout the English-speaking world."]},{"name":"Mary","meanings":["From Old French <i>Marie</i>.  See  <b>Mary</b>   ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1352452,"age":16,"year":"1776","julianDay":2369731,"description":"Thomas Jefferson's American Declaration of Independence endorsed by Congress. Colonies declare independence.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":3083734,"age":17,"year":"1777","julianDay":2370097,"description":"Historical Boundaries: 1777: Chatham, Georgia, United States","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1352454,"age":31,"year":"1791","julianDay":2375210,"description":"Bill of Rights guarantees individual freedom.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1693990,"age":35,"year":"1795","julianDay":2376671,"title":"Yazoo Land Fraud","description":"As Georgia had been weakened during the Revolutionary War, it was unable to defend its Yazoo lands, or land west of the Yazoo River. Thirty-five million acres were sold to four companies for $500,000 as Governor George Mathews signed the Yazoo Act on January 7, 1795. Angry Georgians protested in the streets as they felt bribery and corruption were involved and the sale was far below market value. The legislation tried to rescind the Yazoo Act, but much of the land had been sold to third parties. The issue made its way to the United States Supreme Court and it was determined that rescinding the law was an unconstitutional infringement on a legal contract. The government took full possession of the territory by 1814 and awarded its claimants over $4,000,000.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1352457,"age":48,"year":"1808","julianDay":2381418,"description":"Atlantic slave trade abolished.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1693993,"age":51,"year":"1811","julianDay":2382514,"title":"The Savannah Riots","description":"A barroom brawl in Savannah on Tuesday, November 12, 1811, had international impact. An American seaman boasted of having joined the crew of a French vessel, likely named La Vengeance. Others became upset at the idea of the American joining a foreign nation and a brawl erupted. The county coroner asked for peace but was beaten with clubs. A second clash occurred the following day when French sailors attacked five American seaman. A day after the second attack, twenty French sailors attacked six Americans. Four of them escaped but two were beaten and stabbed. Jacob Taylor died on the scene and a rigger named Collins died the following day. By Friday, a full scale riot erupted when the French crewmen arrested on murder charges were released. Many were arrested and French ships La Vengeance and La Franchise were burned. In the end, the incident caused disruptions in French-American relations and affected shipping and trade.","url":"https://www.jstor.org/stable/40584770?seq=1#metadata_info_tab_contents","urlTitle":"JSTOR - The Savannah Riots: A Burning Issue in Franco-American Hostility","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"MARY Odingsell was born about 1760, in Georgia, United States. She had at least 2 sons and 3 daughters with Isaac Young IV. She lived in Chatham, Georgia, United Stat